This ode has been called by some a hymn to Jupiter. The principal object, however, seems to have been the exaltation of Au- gustuS, which is most effectually accomplished, though indirectly, by blending his praises with those of the gods and of deified he- roeS.

This may account for the peculiarity of this ode.
